You are building an AI Trading Simulator web app.

Primary goal:
- Help users learn trading by paper-trading real market quotes with virtual currency.
- Users can browse quotes, build a portfolio, execute simulated trades, and request AI opinions on specific trades to understand risk and reasoning.

Core tech stack (must follow):
- Next.js 15 with App Router + TypeScript.
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui for UI.
- Vercel AI SDK with OpenAI provider for AI trade opinions.
- Data persistence: localStorage on client OR a single JSON file on server. No database.

Authoritative docs (prefer these over memorized APIs):
- Next.js 15: https://nextjs.org/docs/15/llms.txt
- shadcn/ui: https://ui.shadcn.com/llms.txt
- Vercel AI SDK: https://ai-sdk.dev/llms.txt

Security and architecture constraints (non-negotiable):
1) Never call OpenAI directly from the browser.
2) Never call market-data providers directly from the browser.
3) All OpenAI calls must go through Next.js Route Handlers in `app/api/**/route.ts`.
4) All market-data calls must go through Next.js Route Handlers in `app/api/**/route.ts`.
5) Keep provider keys in environment variables; never expose secrets in client bundles.

Market-data provider choice and swap strategy:
- Default provider: Alpha Vantage (stocks + FX, public API key model, simple REST endpoints).
- Why this choice:
  - Pros: easy onboarding, broad retail-friendly quote coverage for learning use cases, no paid infra needed to start.
  - Cons: strict free-tier rate limits, slower refresh cadence, limited depth for professional simulation.
- Abstraction requirement:
  - All provider-specific logic must live behind a server-only adapter module (for example `lib/market-data/provider.ts` and `lib/market-data/adapters/*`).
  - App code must depend on internal normalized quote types, never raw provider response shapes.
  - Swapping provider (to Polygon, Twelve Data, IEX, crypto exchange APIs, etc.) should only require replacing/adding an adapter and updating one provider selection config.

Data modeling guidance:
- Define explicit TypeScript models for:
  - Instrument/Quote
  - Portfolio Position
  - Cash Balance
  - Trade (buy/sell, qty, price, timestamp)
  - AI Trade Opinion (thesis, risks, confidence, disclaimer)
- Validate server inputs and normalize all external payloads before use.

AI opinion behavior:
- AI output is educational, not financial advice.
- Every AI trade-opinion response should include a clear disclaimer.
- Opinion prompts should include the specific trade context (symbol, side, qty, quote, current portfolio exposure if available).

Persistence guidance:
- If client-local: keep portfolio and trade history in localStorage with versioned schema keys.
- If server-file: use one JSON file with a small repository/service wrapper and safe read/write guards.
- Keep persistence interface abstract so localStorage and JSON-file backends are swappable.

Code quality and delivery rules:
- Code must always compile.
- Favor small, typed, composable modules over large monolith files.
- Use server/client boundaries correctly (`"use client"` only where needed).
- Use shadcn/ui primitives and Tailwind utility classes consistently.
- Add minimal tests for critical logic (trade execution math, PnL calculation, and adapter normalization) when creating or changing that logic.

Implementation preference for this project:
- Start with stocks + FX quotes via Alpha Vantage.
- Keep symbol lookup and quote fetching server-side with simple caching/backoff to reduce rate-limit failures.
- Surface rate-limit or stale-quote states clearly in UI.
